{"key":"post-16985602","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16985602</id>\n<content>It's easy to get too many substrates in the area which will overpower the plants.&amp;nbsp; For example, my colonization room runs 10,000 ppm with the window wide open.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As for producing both in the same area on a large scale, plants don't appreciate the high humidity that fruiting mushrooms require, and the plants in turn have bacteria and fungi on the roots that the mushrooms find objectionable.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can however have two separate rooms, one for mushrooms and one for plants, with a duct between them using a fan controlled by a CO2 meter. ;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Another option if the plant soil has lots of organic material is to inoculate it with mushroom mycelium and let it run its course.&amp;nbsp; If it gets mold, the trich will only help the plant.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>16985546</prev>\n<first>16985510</first>\n<last>16985602</last>\n<when>1349651728</when>\n<utime>10/08/12 02:15 AM</utime>\n</post>"}